You can&#39;t stop a forEach...
use the find method.

    const getConnection = function(cid){
     return allEvents.find(event =&gt; event.connectionId == cid);
    }

```getConnection``` does not return anything. [find](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/find) is what you need:


```
const getConnection = function(cid){
    return allEvents.find(event =&gt; {
        return event.connectionId === cid;
    });
}
```

That&#39;s because in `getConnection` you are returning inside of the `forEach` callback. You&#39;ll have to use `find` and return the value that&#39;s *found* from the *find* method

```
const getConnection = function(cid){
    return allEvents.find(event =&gt; {
        if(event.connectionId == cid){
           // console.log(event)
            return event
        }
    });
}
```

Returning from an inner function doesn&#39;t magically return from the enclosing function. You&#39;re only returning from `forEach` (which doesn&#39;t make sense since forEach returns undefined). `forEach` also isn&#39;t the right choice here, what you wanted to use was `find`


    const getConnection = function(cid){
        return allEvents.find(event =&gt; event.connectionId === cid);
    }

